Q: How did stress testing start, and how has it evolved?

A: Stress testing began as a response to the reforms following the Global Financial Crisis and has been an important element of the Board's regulatory framework and supervisory program since 2009. Over the years, there has been a commitment to improving the transparency of stress tests and reducing the volatility of resulting capital buffer requirements. This evolution reflects a continuous effort to enhance the understanding of how to maintain the strength of the financial system by ensuring that large supervised institutions have sufficient capital to absorb losses and continue lending, even during economic downturns.

